02:55.669 --> 02:57.002
Hey, where are you going?

02:57.004 --> 02:58.770
Back to the dry cleaner.
Look at this.

02:58.772 --> 03:01.240
They didn't get the stain
out of my Starfleet uniform.

03:01.242 --> 03:04.276
Well, if you didn't make me wear
the green body paint in bed,

03:04.278 --> 03:07.279
you wouldn't have to get it
dry-cleaned so much.

03:07.281 --> 03:09.181
Nah, it's worth it.

03:10.551 --> 03:11.783
(Skype ringtone playing)

03:11.785 --> 03:13.151
Hey, wait, it's your mom.

03:13.153 --> 03:16.088
Oh, too bad.
She just missed me!

03:19.527 --> 03:20.859
Hey, Beverly.

03:20.861 --> 03:22.361
Oh, hello, Penny.

03:22.363 --> 03:23.562
Uh, Leonard just left.

03:23.564 --> 03:25.864
He's gonna be so upset
he missed your call.

03:25.866 --> 03:27.599
Why?

03:27.601 --> 03:29.468
Because he...

03:29.470 --> 03:30.802
Yeah, I don't know.

03:30.804 --> 03:32.838
How are you?

03:32.840 --> 03:35.274
Did you mean personally
or professionally?

03:35.276 --> 03:36.775
Um, personally?

03:36.777 --> 03:38.844
Like, what'd you do last night?

03:38.846 --> 03:41.113
I had Cuban food
at the home of a man

03:41.115 --> 03:45.117
with whom I shared
unsatisfying intercourse.

03:46.954 --> 03:49.521
Wow. Okay.

03:51.258 --> 03:53.659
And to anticipate
your next questions,

03:53.661 --> 03:56.929
roasted pork
and sideways missionary.

03:59.466 --> 04:02.935
Sure. Sure.
'Cause you were full.

04:05.039 --> 04:07.806
I haven't looked
at all this stuff in years.

04:07.808 --> 04:09.141
Had it.

04:09.143 --> 04:10.676
Had it.

04:10.678 --> 04:13.579
Burnt down my garage with it.

04:13.581 --> 04:15.647
I had three model rockets
as a kid,

04:15.649 --> 04:18.649
and that was the largest
space program in India.

04:18.652 --> 04:22.254
You have a replica Saturn V?

04:22.256 --> 04:25.257
Yeah. My dad bought it
before he, you know,

04:25.259 --> 04:27.192
abandoned our family.

04:27.194 --> 04:29.294
Lucky duck.

04:29.296 --> 04:34.099
Could never bring myself to
open it without him. (chuckles)

04:34.101 --> 04:35.701
It's silly.

04:35.703 --> 04:36.835
No, it's not silly.

04:36.837 --> 04:38.904
I always wanted my dad
to build rockets with me,

04:38.906 --> 04:41.239
but he wasn't interested.

04:41.241 --> 04:42.708
Ah, yes, disappointing
fathers.

04:42.710 --> 04:44.109
Tell me about it.

04:44.111 --> 04:47.179
I remember for my 16th birthday,
my dad bought me a Mercedes.

04:47.181 --> 04:50.382
Like, a little one,
like a starter Mercedes.

04:51.819 --> 04:52.985
He had barely handed me the keys

04:52.987 --> 04:54.720
before he had
to rush back to work.

04:54.722 --> 04:57.990
I didn't see him again till,
like, pretty late that night.

05:00.794 --> 05:02.661
Anyway...

05:04.064 --> 05:07.766
...as angry as I was
with him leaving,

05:07.768 --> 05:09.935
building this stuff
is probably what led me

05:09.937 --> 05:11.470
to become an engineer.

05:11.472 --> 05:13.705
I suppose, in his own way,

05:13.707 --> 05:15.707
my dad also encouraged me
to pursue science.

05:15.709 --> 05:17.542
I mean, he is the one
that taught me

05:17.544 --> 05:19.811
that flatulence
is combustible.

05:20.881 --> 05:24.816
And also, polyester
gym shorts don't burn.

05:24.818 --> 05:26.318
They melt.

05:28.022 --> 05:30.055
Yeah, I guess I'm an
astrophysicist because,

05:30.057 --> 05:32.524
as a kid, I said I like
to look at the stars,

05:32.526 --> 05:35.727
so my dad sent me to Hawaii
to visit the Keck telescope.

05:38.532 --> 05:40.699
Screw you. My pain is real.

05:44.405 --> 05:47.005
You know what?
Forget the past.

05:47.007 --> 05:50.275
What do you say you and
me build this rocket?

05:50.277 --> 05:52.010
That sounds like
it could be

05:52.012 --> 05:53.845
a real bonding
experience for us.

05:53.847 --> 05:54.880
Right?

05:54.882 --> 05:55.847
Oh, I see.

05:55.849 --> 05:58.050
Oh, you think
that's a positive.

06:02.189 --> 06:04.956
So, you don't want to hang out
with Sheldon and Howard?

06:04.958 --> 06:07.492
No, they were bonding
over their sad childhoods,

06:07.494 --> 06:11.363
and my stupid parents
were always there for me.

06:12.599 --> 06:13.932
What's all this?

06:13.934 --> 06:16.134
I'm just boxing up all
the clothes Halley's outgrown.

06:16.136 --> 06:18.103
Guess we won't
need them anymore.

06:18.105 --> 06:19.438
Oh, well, slow down.

06:19.440 --> 06:21.440
I'm sure there's some
you could reuse for a boy.

06:21.442 --> 06:24.609
“Daddy's little girl”?

06:24.611 --> 06:27.279
Okay, well, what if we, uh,
change it to say,

06:27.281 --> 06:29.748
“Daddy's little girl magnet”?

06:29.750 --> 06:31.550
Boom! Boy shirt.

06:33.420 --> 06:34.586
What about this?

06:34.588 --> 06:35.954
Uh, okay.

06:35.956 --> 06:38.457
Uh, pull off the skirt, slap
a lightning bolt on the front,

06:38.459 --> 06:40.192
and you got baby Flash.

06:40.194 --> 06:41.393
Ooh.

06:41.395 --> 06:42.594
Stick a long sleeve under it.

06:42.596 --> 06:44.963
Boom! Baby Sheldon.

06:46.500 --> 06:48.166
Wow, you're really good at this.

06:48.168 --> 06:49.301
Oh, please.

06:49.303 --> 06:50.535
This isn't my first time

06:50.537 --> 06:53.205
turning girl clothes
into boy clothes.

06:54.181 --> 06:57.115
Why? You got your sister's
hand-me-downs?

06:57.117 --> 07:00.452
Yeah, that.

07:03.757 --> 07:06.725
Oh. I should've
brought peanuts.

07:06.727 --> 07:08.760
You can't eat peanuts.
You're allergic.

07:08.762 --> 07:11.963
If you die, who's going
to drive me home?

07:11.965 --> 07:13.531
I'm not gonna eat them.

07:13.533 --> 07:15.066
It's a thing
they do at JPL.

07:15.068 --> 07:17.135
When the Ranger mission finally
had a successful launch,

07:17.137 --> 07:18.436
there were peanuts
in the room.

07:18.438 --> 07:21.206
Ever since then,
they have them at every launch.

07:21.208 --> 07:23.808
That sounds like
a silly superstition.

07:23.810 --> 07:26.277
It's more of a tradition.

07:26.279 --> 07:28.713
Oh! I do love a tradition.

07:28.715 --> 07:32.383
Could you pull over
at the next peanut store?

07:32.385 --> 07:35.353
I don't think
that's a real thing.

07:35.355 --> 07:36.721
Oh, don't be pedantic.

07:36.723 --> 07:38.356
Any nut store will do.

07:38.358 --> 07:42.794
I-I don't think we can
get peanuts out here.

07:42.796 --> 07:46.131
Ah, well, then
this whole day's ruined.

07:46.133 --> 07:50.135
Now that I think about it, maybe
it is more of a superstition.

07:50.137 --> 07:51.870
Whew! That was close.

07:56.510 --> 07:58.643
(ringtone playing)

08:00.447 --> 08:03.414
Oh, uh, hey, Beverly, you called
my phone, not Leonard's.

08:03.416 --> 08:06.484
Actually, I was hoping
to speak with you.

08:06.486 --> 08:08.119
Is this a good time?

08:08.121 --> 08:09.954
Uh, that depends.

08:09.956 --> 08:11.656
What time is it where you are?

08:11.658 --> 08:12.824
Uh, just after 5:00.

08:12.826 --> 08:15.126
(clears throat)
Yeah, that counts.

08:15.128 --> 08:17.662
What's up?

08:17.664 --> 08:20.999
Well, I enjoyed our conversation
the other day,

08:21.001 --> 08:23.067
and I was hoping to continue it.

08:23.069 --> 08:24.269
Really?

08:24.271 --> 08:26.571
Uh, yes. You may
find this surprising,

08:26.573 --> 08:29.841
but I don't have a lot of
what you would call girlfriends.

08:29.843 --> 08:33.711
(exaggerated):
What?

08:33.712 --> 08:37.115
Of course, there are
my female colleagues,

08:37.116 --> 08:39.049
but, uh, they're all Freudians,

08:39.052 --> 08:42.554
so the only boy that I can
dish about is my father.

08:42.556 --> 08:44.856
(laughs)

08:48.762 --> 08:50.024
Uh, well, you know,
I'm here for you.

08:50.025 --> 08:51.424
What do you want to talk about?

08:51.426 --> 08:54.627
Well, last time,
we focused on my life.

08:54.629 --> 08:56.496
If we're going to be
real girlfriends,

08:56.498 --> 08:58.197
we should talk about you
as well.

08:58.199 --> 08:59.632
Well, you know,
if we're gonna be

08:59.634 --> 09:01.668
real girlfriends,
we should get a third girl

09:01.670 --> 09:04.470
we can trash behind her back.

09:04.472 --> 09:07.307
Oh, so we'd be catty.

09:07.309 --> 09:10.043
Oh, I like it.

09:10.045 --> 09:12.111
What about Sheldon's fiancée?

09:12.113 --> 09:15.081
She seems a bit dour.

09:15.083 --> 09:17.784
Ooh, “dour.”

09:17.786 --> 09:19.485
Meow.

09:23.625 --> 09:24.924
All right.

09:24.926 --> 09:26.292
Here we go.

09:26.294 --> 09:28.561
L-minus ten, nine...

09:28.563 --> 09:30.797
Wait, what are you doing?
It's “T-minus”"

09:30.799 --> 09:33.366
I was an astronaut.
We used L-minus.

09:33.368 --> 09:35.368
But this is a Saturn V,

09:35.370 --> 09:36.903
and when they launched those,
they said “T-minus”"

09:36.905 --> 09:40.173
It's my rocket!
We're doing it my way.

09:40.175 --> 09:42.675
Fine.

09:44.112 --> 09:46.012
I'm not saying
I know why your dad left,

09:46.014 --> 09:48.314
but I think I'm getting an idea.

09:50.185 --> 09:51.284
L-minus

09:51.286 --> 09:53.219
ten, nine, eight,

09:53.221 --> 09:54.487
seven, six...

09:54.489 --> 09:58.191
'Cause you're
kind of bossy.

09:58.193 --> 10:01.227
...five, four, three, two,

10:01.229 --> 10:02.695
one...

10:06.701 --> 10:09.836
I remember them
going up higher.

